<div id="review_156952473" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/156952473" />
    <a title="Jojo A" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4882515-jojo-a"><img alt="Jojo A" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1332835515p2/4882515.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/156952473?book_show_action=true">Mar 26, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jojo A" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jojo A" href="/user/show/4882515-jojo-a">Jojo A</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780007848423" href="/book/show/10751801-the-monk-who-sold-his-ferrari">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer156952473" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18208993803386261793">What can I say about this book. At the very begining of it I was glad to read it because it had triggered many bad habits I was doing related to my thinking which awakened me. However, I was doing 3/4 of what Julian was talking about, so I was more familiar with what he mentioned or tired to convey.<br/><br/>The story if fanatic which is produced in a phsycological analysis. It&apos;s yes inspirational, but come on! They made the 10 ritual habits so easy to do which is not, when I reached the half of the book </span>
  <span id="freeText18208993803386261793" style="display:none">What can I say about this book. At the very begining of it I was glad to read it because it had triggered many bad habits I was doing related to my thinking which awakened me. However, I was doing 3/4 of what Julian was talking about, so I was more familiar with what he mentioned or tired to convey.<br /><br />The story if fanatic which is produced in a phsycological analysis. It's yes inspirational, but come on! They made the 10 ritual habits so easy to do which is not, when I reached the half of the book it seemed impossible. I mean there are stuff which are yes we can change about ourselves! But it's not as easy the book says especially when it's driven from a story that we don't know either those people exist or don't (Sages of Sivana), I reckon motivation books like this must be based on stories which are true so we can really use facts in our daily lives and not fool ourselves. <br /><br />I have reached almost the end of the book and I am getting bored, I don't know if the conclusion will be phenonmenon.<br /><br />I was only curious about this book because everyone was talking about it and Paulo Coelho has left his recommendation on the cover of this book! Which I don't really don't know now if this was only commercial purpose! I don't hate the book but the way the materials preseneted can awaken you, yes, but to change you? I doubt.<br /><br />The Title of the book is much more interesting than the content.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18208993803386261793" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


